<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-12-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="788" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d788">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bowen</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Caracas</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-02"><hi rend="italic">December 2,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Bowen states that it seems to him the questions at issue can be
                            satisfactorily settled diplomatically by Germany and by arbitration by
                            Great Britain without rupture of relations.</p>
                        <p>Mr. Bowen requests permission to use his good offices in an endeavor to
                            prevent rupture of relations.)</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>